Last year, we learned that we=E2=80=99re far from any new normal. The statu=
s quo isn=E2=80=99t
working: The majority of luxury goods being sold are ugly, too expensive, o=
r unoriginal. So executives are forced to shake things up. Here=E2=80=99s w=
hat we=E2=80=99ll experience in 2025, in the aftermath of one of the indust=
ry=E2=80=99s toughest years ever.=C2=A0

1. Designers Will Design Again
------------------------------

There=E2=80=99s been much ado about the number of designer exits and
appointments in 2024, but I wasn=E2=80=99t shocked. First off, rapid turnov=
er isn=E2=80=99t new, we just have more access to incremental information t=
han ever before. And when things aren=E2=80=99t working, change is necessar=
y. Even Arnault, who tends to stick with designers long after their sell-by=
 date=E2=80=94a mix of loyalty, stubbornness, paranoia, and a brand-first w=
orldview=E2=80=94made some changes. If the rumblings at Dior and Fendi are =
any indication, there will be more to come at LVMH in the second half of 20=
25.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

For now, though, expect executives to direct designers to focus on collecti=
ons, not the advertising or merchandising that supports them. Matthieu Blaz=
y=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cartistic director of fashion activities=E2=80=9D title=
 at Chanel, where he=E2=80=99ll debut his first collection in October, is a=
 telltale sign that he will prioritize capital-F Fashion over other more co=
mmercial endeavors. Sarah
Burton=E2=80=99s appointment at Givenchy and John Galliano=E2=80=99s succes=
s at Margiela (and expected return to the LVMH fold) are also early example=
s of this trend, a flat-out rejection of the idea that designers are market=
ers, too. (With the clarity of hindsight, of course, these are two entirely=
 separate disciplines=E2=80=A6)=C2=A0

=C2=A0

The tricky part is that different brands require different types of creativ=
e
leadership. Jonathan Anderson was successful at Loewe because he was so dee=
ply involved in every aspect of building the brand. If he is headed to a ma=
chine like Dior, where he will inevitably have less control, will he be as =
effective? Or satisfied?

2. A Looming Ops
Crisis
----------------

If the industry wants to convince design leaders to keep their heads in the=
 studio,
executives will need to assuage their nerves and amplify their vision with =
strong and reliable operators behind them. The problem, of course, is that =
there is a paucity of business talent at work today=E2=80=94particularly as=
 traditional sales and marketing channels continue to evolve. In fact, the =
next generation of fashion, retail, and luxury C.E.O.s barely exists, which=
 helps to explain why Arnault=E2=80=99s children have risen so quickly up t=
he LVMH ranks. (Nepotism is only 80 percent of it.) Gucci,
Kering=E2=80=99s largest and most challenged brand, is being run by a first=
-time C.E.O. who mostly worked in communications and marketing: a once unco=
nventional, now increasingly common path. But fashion is marketing, which i=
s another reason why this whole return to the traditional designer feels fl=
eeting.

3. Hollywood Tries to
Crack Fashion (Again)
---------------------

This week, I conducted a brief, unscientific survey to see if
rank-and-file industry people were feeling the effects of the Pinault famil=
y office=E2=80=99s acquisition of CAA, which closed in late 2023. For most,=
 it=E2=80=99s been business as usual. =E2=80=9CCampaigns are still happenin=
g, and those brands are still calling the same people,=E2=80=9D one agency =
insider told me. =E2=80=9CZendaya is getting the campaign wherever she is=
=E2=80=A6 CAA or not.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

That=E2=80=99s not surprising: These are large
businesses that need to work together, and a new owner won=E2=80=99t change=
 that, especially given that both Hollywood and fashion are relationship bu=
sinesses. The bigger issue is that the entertainment industry still hasn=E2=
=80=99t figured out how to make money in fashion, outside of actors working=
 on campaigns. (Contrast that with beauty, where Rhode and Rare are bluepri=
nts for success.) One executive predicted we=E2=80=99re going to see an inf=
lux of celebrity food brands. But still, =E2=80=9CRyan Reynolds
and Selena Gomez are unicorns,=E2=80=9D another person told me. =E2=80=9CTh=
e celeb component at this point is table stakes. You need a serious operato=
r. What=E2=80=99s the product angle? And who=E2=80=99s going to actually ma=
rket it? [Successful brands] only work because that person is genuinely inv=
ested. Not because someone at an agency put a room together and decided tha=
t person needs a brand.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

