Again, there is a dearth of real operators in fashion. Skims, and this year=
=E2=80=99s
inevitable I.P.O. of that business, only works with Kim Kardashian and the =
Gredes behind the scenes.=C2=A0

4. The Multibrand
Blow-Up Lingers=E2=80=A6
------------------

In 2024, Matches shut down. Farfetch was acquired by Coupang. Mytheresa bro=
kered a
deal to acquire Yoox Net-a-Porter Group. Saks bought Neiman Marcus Group. T=
he Nordstrom family finally got the chance to take the American department =
store private. Selfridges, one of the last great department stores, suffere=
d losses. There=E2=80=99s still plenty of competition in multibrand retail,=
 and brands continue to make more product than they can sell, which means t=
hat competitive pricing will continue to reign supreme this year. But the d=
ownsizing in this space will undeniably
impact consumers. Expect store closures and refreshed concepts, as well as =
a few new, inspired entrants creeping into the space to take advantage of t=
he ennui. People want to go shopping. It=E2=80=99s up to these stores to fi=
gure out what to carry=E2=80=94online and off.

5. More M&A
-----------

Expect a string of smaller investments announced in early 2025, alongside t=
he
inevitable big acquisitions that will follow the dissolution of the Tapestr=
y-Capri deal. The industry is still consolidating and will need to continue=
 to do so, especially given the lack of operational talent floating around.=
 This isn=E2=80=99t simply about the new Trump administration, or the end o=
f the Lina Khan era. The oscillations of the retail and D.T.C. businesses, =
multiplied by shallower moats for new brands, means that the consolidation =
of the industry must
continue.

6. Trump
Smooching
---------

Like so many other creative industries, formerly #resistance-friendly,
Trump-detesting industry leaders will bite their tongues this time around, =
either because they are exhausted or because they understandably fear his t=
ariff threats. On the luxury side, executives seem to be less worried about=
 the president-elect than about whether a post-inflation rebound in consume=
r spending will occur in the second half of 2025. The Arnaults, in particul=
ar, are playing offense, as they must: They see Trump as an old familiar ty=
pe with whom they can negotiate. For mall brands
with slim margins, there is more of an immediate threat from the cost of ra=
w materials and imported goods. Fashion=E2=80=99s biggest mistake would be =
to underestimate Trump, or to fall into the trap of thinking he won=E2=80=
=99t do the things he=E2=80=99s saying he wants to do.=C2=A0

7. Things Will Get
Worse Before They Get Better
----------------------------

One of the most important conversations I had this year was with a former K=
ering
executive. This person reminded me that the years after the Great Recession=
 and its hangover=E2=80=942012, 2013, 2014=E2=80=94were not easy for luxury=
=2E The resurgence only started in 2015=
 with Alessandro, Demna, et al. In Hol=
lywood, the post-Covid, post-strike mantra has been Survive Until 2025. For=
 fashion, it=E2=80=99s more like Survive Until 2027. I=E2=80=99m not of the=
 mind that we=E2=80=99ve reached peak anything in the luxury industry; peop=
le are fed up with prices and choices
right now, but there will be good times again. However, a lot of structural=
 issues need to change before we get there. Companies need to stoke desire=
=E2=80=94a concept they lost sight of in the fat years of complacency=E2=80=
=94through products and concepts that consumers believe possess inherent va=
lue. And those consumers need to feel they aren=E2=80=99t getting hosed. Ev=
en then, it=E2=80=99ll be different than it was before.=C2=A0

=E2=80=8A

Endnotes=E2=80=A6
-----------

On Monday morning, after waking up (naturally) at 5:15 a.m. and
running the Silver Lake reservoir loop (yes, I=E2=80=99m bragging), I stood=
 in line at Courage Bagels on Virgil Avenue for approximately 15 minutes. I=
 don=E2=80=99t like queues, but I do like observing people. (Bagels that do=
n=E2=80=99t feel like a weight at the bottom of your stomach are pretty goo=
d, too. The crowd was mostly locals.)=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Some field notes: One guy was wearing a green Aim=C3=A9 Leon Dore hoodie (a=
lmost a classic at
this point?); another was in a black beanie, bad jeans, and Mephistos; one =
woman was wearing a fuschia puffer and carrying a cross-body bag made from =
what could only be a Millennium Falcon pillowcase (only in Los Angeles); on=
e lady was wearing a mask. There was one little kid=E2=80=A6 dressed up in =
a magician=E2=80=99s costume (I guess that was his reward for standing in l=
ine). My biggest observation, however, is that it may be time to jump ship =
on Salomon sneakers unless you are very, very confident.
Or at least put them on a shelf for a little while. They feel too fashion.=
=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Until Monday,

Lauren=C2=A0

