argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">There=E2=80=99s been much ado about the number =
of designer exits and
appointments in 2024, but I wasn=E2=80=99t shocked. First off, rapid turnov=
er isn=E2=80=99t new, we just have more access to incremental information t=
han ever before. And when things aren=E2=80=99t working, change is necessar=
y. Even Arnault, who tends to stick with designers long after their sell-by=
 date=E2=80=94a mix of loyalty, stubbornness, paranoia, and a brand-first w=
orldview=E2=80=94made some changes. If the rumblings at Dior and Fendi are =
any indication, there will be more to come at LVMH in the second half of 20=
25.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D=
"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">For now, though, expect executives to direct =
designers to focus on <em>collections</em>, not the advertising or merchand=
ising that supports them. <strong>Matthieu Blazy</strong>=E2=80=99s =E2=80=
=9Cartistic director of fashion activities=E2=80=9D title at Chanel, where =
he=E2=80=99ll debut his first collection in October, is a telltale sign tha=
t he will prioritize capital-F Fashion over other more commercial endeavors=
=2E <strong>Sarah
