argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">This week, I conducted a brief, unscientific su=
rvey to see if
rank-and-file industry people were feeling the effects of the <strong>Pinau=
lt</strong> family office=E2=80=99s acquisition of CAA, which closed in lat=
e 2023. For most, it=E2=80=99s been business as usual. =E2=80=9CCampaigns a=
re still happening, and those brands are still calling the same people,=E2=
=80=9D one agency insider told me. =E2=80=9C<strong>Zendaya</strong> is get=
ting the campaign wherever she is=E2=80=A6 CAA or not.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p=
 style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Tha=
t=E2=80=99s not surprising: These are large
businesses that need to work together, and a new owner won=E2=80=99t change=
 that, especially given that both Hollywood and fashion are relationship bu=
sinesses. The bigger issue is that the entertainment industry still hasn=E2=
=80=99t figured out how to make money in fashion, outside of actors working=
 on campaigns. (Contrast that with beauty, where Rhode and Rare are bluepri=
nts for success.) One executive predicted we=E2=80=99re going to see an inf=
lux of celebrity food brands. But still, =E2=80=9C<strong>Ryan Reynolds</st=
rong>
and <strong>Selena Gomez</strong> are unicorns,=E2=80=9D another person tol=
d me. =E2=80=9CThe celeb component at this point is table stakes. You need =
a serious operator. What=E2=80=99s the product angle? And who=E2=80=99s goi=
ng to actually market it? [Successful brands] only work because that person=
 is genuinely invested. Not because someone at an agency put a room togethe=
r and decided that person needs a brand.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p></div>
