argin:0;">Like so many other creative industries, formerly #resistance-frie=
ndly,
Trump-detesting industry leaders will bite their tongues this time around, =
either because they are exhausted or because they understandably fear his t=
ariff threats. On the luxury side, executives seem to be less worried about=
 the president-elect than about whether a post-inflation rebound in consume=
r spending will occur in the second half of 2025. The Arnaults, in particul=
ar, are playing offense, as they must: They see Trump as an old familiar ty=
pe with whom they can negotiate. For mall brands
with slim margins, there is more of an immediate threat from the cost of ra=
w materials and imported goods. Fashion=E2=80=99s biggest mistake would be =
to underestimate Trump, or to fall into the trap of thinking he won=E2=80=
=99t do the things he=E2=80=99s saying he wants to do.=C2=A0</p></div>
