ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;">One of the most important conversations I had this year was with =
a former Kering
executive. This person reminded me that the years after the Great Recession=
 and its hangover=E2=80=942012, 2013, 2014=E2=80=94were not easy for luxury=
=2E The resurgence only started in 2015=
 with <strong>Alessandro</strong>, <st=
rong>Demna</strong>, <em>et al</em>. In Hollywood, the post-Covid, post-str=
ike mantra has been Survive Until 2025. For fashion, it=E2=80=99s more like=
 Survive Until 2027. I=E2=80=99m not of the mind that we=E2=80=99ve reached=
 peak <em>anything</em> in the luxury industry; people are fed up with pric=
es and choices
right now, but there will be good times again. However, a lot of structural=
 issues need to change before we get there. Companies need to stoke desire=
=E2=80=94a concept they lost sight of in the fat years of complacency=E2=80=
=94through products and concepts that consumers believe possess inherent va=
lue. And those consumers need to feel they aren=E2=80=99t getting hosed. Ev=
en then, it=E2=80=99ll be different than it was before.=C2=A0</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
